ic plates. Yet the plates did not always sit still, and it is events on their colliding boundaries that account for familiar Christian controversies in novel ways. What Makes a Church Sacred? argues that scholarship misunderstands well-known religious figures by ignoring the legal issues they faced. In this seminal text, Farag nuances the scholarly conversations on sacred space, gift-giving, wealth, and poverty in the late antique Mediterranean world, making use not only of Latin and Greek sources, but also Coptic and Arabic evidence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aChristianity and culturezRome. 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aChurch property (Canon law). 0aChurch propertyxLaw and legislationxHistory. 0aChurch propertyxLaw and legislationzRome. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107391520 cprintz978052038200840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520382015zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520382015zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520382015/original  a978-3-11-073915-2 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA